##Wuhan Newborns and a 72-hour rescue

Wechat media-fox

Features, for those who insist on serious reading options. Sohu News Extreme Day studio.

ABSTRACT: Yan chengang was born the day before the "city closure" in Wuhan. He was soon found to have severe Pilo Syndrome and needed surgical treatment. He was transferred from Wuhan to Nanjing within 72 hours by civil volunteers, two local hospitals, three provincial government departments in Hubei, Anhui and Jiangsu, and the media.

Wen Gaojia intern Zhao Jiajia

Editor Lin Pang

Yan Chenggang was born the day before the "blockade" in Wuhan, suffering from a rare congenital disease —— Florida Syndrome. He's got a tiny windpipe, which means he's breathing. In the city of Wuhan, his father, Yan Yiwei, could not find a doctor to operate on him.

Shen Weimin, a doctor at the Children's Hospital affiliated to Nanjing Medical University, offered to treat him, provided Yan somehow managed to get the child to Nanjing. In the early spring of 2020, the 1,000 Mile Journey from Wuhan to Nanjing was long and heavily fortified.

On February 18, Yan posted a message to friends asking for help. Volunteer Chen Xingxu started contacting Yan on the morning of February 21, taking over the first leg of the rescue. By the morning of Feb. 24, Yan chengang had left Wuhan for nearly 72 hours.

After the volunteers, members of the Huazhong University of Science and Technology, government departments in Hubei, Anhui and Jiangsu, and the media were also involved in the rescue. Seventy-two hours later, Yan Chenggang, a month old, was on a bus to Nanjing.

This is the Wuhan "closed city" in the few successful referral outside the province of non-new coronary pneumonia patients. For the volunteers, it was a chance to make up for the more unresolved and pent-up emotions they had experienced over the past month. On March 4, the Children's Hospital affiliated to Nanjing Medical University prepared to perform an operation on Yan Chengang, a child with a brand-new life. Now he can finally save enough energy to face his illness.

Born the day before the siege

When Yan chengang's child was born, there was no lively scene. Originally, when he opened his eyes in the ward of Hubei Provincial Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine, several smiling faces appeared to him. His father, Yan Yiwei, welcomed his first child, grandma, and aunt, at the age of 37, and all the other relatives were ready to come and see him.

On January 22, the National Health Commission announced that 444 new cases of pneumonia had been confirmed in Hubei Province. That morning, the fever clinic of the Provincial Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine had nearly 10 patients waiting for treatment. The doctors had changed into protective gear and beads of water had formed on their masks. When Yan's mother was admitted to the hospital in the afternoon, his father bought four N90 masks for 120 yuan and stayed outside the delivery room with his grandmother.

At 9:40 pm, there was more noise and tension in the hospital than usual, but Yan was glad to see his son open his eyes and look around. After the cry passed 12 hours, Wuhan ushered in the "closure" of the news.

The Child Yan Chengang who feels strange to everything in the world probably can not feel the fear of the virus that wreaks havoc in the city. If he can get out of the hospital in good health, he will, like many children born during the epidemic, spend the first untroubled years of his life almost unscathed. Later, he will have a vague idea of his birth date, the beginning of the 2020s, and perhaps why people call his city the city of heroes. It was supposed to happen a long time later, but now fate seemed eager to let him know in advance.

On the night of his birth, Yan Yiwei discovered that "he breathed out of his mouth when he breathed. " The next morning, he saw again, "he was Pale, and his lips were purple. "

Yan chengang suffered from a rare congenital disease. On the first day of the "closure of the city" in Wuhan, he was transferred to the Hubei provincial maternal and child health hospital. Doctors confirmed that he was a child with cleft palate, but the hospital had no specialist to perform the operation, and he was under constant observation in the neonatal intensive care unit.

Yan Yiwei ran across the road to the Wuhan University Stomatological Hospital, where the nurse on duty to find a doctor to see, but they can do nothing, this disease is special, "know too few people. "

He felt powerless. "I wanted to do something for him [ the child ] , but it seemed like I had to leave it to chance. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Picture shows Yan chengang, a child born before the full moon

To make matters worse, on January 30, the hospital called and said, "during the outbreak, in order to be safe, and because the beds there were also very nervous, we had to bring the baby back. " The day the baby was brought back, she was in complete shock -- she could only feed her son about 5 ml through a tube a week after he was born -- and she choked on milk, spilling it out of her nose and mouth. He could only breathe with his mouth open, and there was a hoarse voice in his throat all the time, and he had no energy at all.

Due to the shortage of medical resources and other reasons, non-pneumonia diseases during the epidemic, regardless of the size of the disease, the risk level is even higher than usual.

Chen Xingxu, founder of the 520 volunteer group, a non-governmental Organization, has been trying to find beds for new pneumonia patients. He collected nearly 200 messages a day from people seeking help from Weibo pneumonia patients. After February 9, Wuhan began to implement new pneumonia "four categories of personnel" classification centralized management measures, to February 14, the number of patients with pneumonia to reduce to 30.

More non-pneumonia patients fill the call. "In fact, such patients have been asking for help, but they have been inundated with requests from pneumonia patients. " Lu Qing and friends launched a "don't give red envelopes volunteer group" on Feb. 11 to help non-pneumonia patients, "A lot of them are telling themselves that they can wait a little longer, but at this point, some critically ill patients can't wait. "

February 18th, yan Yiwei sent a friend circle for help: "The baby was only born more than 20 days, according to the preliminary diagnosis of Pilo Syndrome, at present because of breathing difficulties + feeding difficulties, has on non-invasive Suction Machine... life-threatening, urgent need surgery. "

A friend posted it on his twitter feed.

The Post has been retweeted more than 1,000 times. The member of the "don't give Red Envelopes Volunteer Group" , Yu Hang, saw his friends all turning on his Weibo home page. At the end of the appeal, "Save my little baby, " Yan's father wrote. "KNOCK! KNOCK AGAIN! Knock three times! "

He called right away, "The father was a little choked up. His child needed to be transferred to the Children's Hospital affiliated to Nanjing Medical University for an operation, but the children's hospital needed him to show the results of the nucleic acid test. But neither the child nor he had symptoms of fever and could not get the quota of nucleic acid test. Even if the quota was given, the waiting time for the result would normally exceed 24 hours. He was worried that the child could not wait any longer. "

Normally, the astronauts would gather information for help on microblogs. Each day, they would contact four to five patients, ask them about their condition and the help they needed, and tell them about the official hospital information for non-pneumonia patients, answer the referral procedures, and then put the patient information into the form, follow-up. At present, the "No red envelopes volunteer group" includes more than 110 non-pneumonia patients. The critically ill patients who have been verified will be reported to CCTV news reporters, cCTV news announced on February 15 the help-seeking information platform that patients with critical illness can fill out.

"young children, or elderly people living alone, in urgent cases will be given priority in the treatment of critical illness. " After hearing Yan's case, the astronaut asked Yan Yiwei to provide the community telephone number and the child's identity card number, wanted to file a critical illness report. But Yan Yiwei told the astronaut: "The child does not have the ID card. "

I only had a three-minute conversation with Yan, but the astronaut remembers him. "because of the epidemic, the baby has difficulty even obtaining a legal identity. " When it was finally reported, the column of Yan's identity card was blank. In a note, Yu wrote: This is a newborn baby.

The problem of off-site referral

Before the birth of the child, Yan Yiwei's wife had regular monthly check-ups. Chromosomes, NT, size abnormalities, blocking antibodies were all done. After the birth of the child, "The child has Pilo's syndrome, a chromosomal problem, and even in the United States, it takes a very experienced doctor to detect it with a 50 percent chance, " the doctor told Yan

Pirow Syndrome is characterized by MICROGNATHIA, drop of the tongue, cleft palate and aspiration obstruction. "The doctor said the child's Trachea is extremely narrow, only 2.5 mm, and the normal baby is 3.5-4 mm. " Yan posted on the Forum for help, he was advised to consult a leading expert in the field -- a doctor at the Nanjing Medical University, after an online consultation, Feb. 1, "It's the small jaw (Pirow syndrome) , " Shen replied. "The Oxygenation is down to 70 percent, so surgery is definitely needed. "

"The child's condition is complicated, the surgery is risky and the prognosis is unknown, " Shen told extreme day. So he has to survive the surgery, improve his breathing, and then perhaps deal with various complications.

But with the outbreak, it just got worse. According to the procedure for referral during the outbreak in Wuhan, patients and accompanying staff are required to undergo nucleic acid testing, issue a "non-pneumonia health certificate" , apply for a pass for the vehicles from Han, and register with the local epidemic prevention headquarters at the receiving hospital.

On the evening of February 20, Chen Xingxu, the founder of the 520 volunteer team, also saw Yan's appeal for help. He had followed a patient who had been successfully referred to Beijing and was familiar with the procedures needed for a referral to another place.

The next morning, when Chen called, the man at the other end of the line, Yan Yiwei, nearly collapsed. "I asked him a question, and he kept going on and on about it, answering questions that had nothing to do with it, " Chen said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Volunteer Chen Xingxu (right) carries supplies to the hospital. Photo courtesy of the respondents

When Chen Xingxu was looking for a bed for a patient with pneumonia, he scoured the Internet for the phone numbers of relevant government workers and also collected some "useful" contact information. Knowing that at present the child is in a fragile condition and needs to be evacuated by an ambulance, Chen Xingxu called a person in charge of the relevant department, "He was driving and the phone was disconnected four or five times, " he said. "He told me on the spot that he would follow up. "

Before noon, Yan received calls from the street offices, the Jiangxia District and Wuhan Public Security bureaus, "You can leave Wuhan, " They told Chen. "Women and children in the province agreed to send ambulances, but they could not leave Hubei. They could only take them to Huangmei County, on the border between Anhui and Hubei. "

At around 3:00 p.m. , the astronaut received a telephone call from Yan Yiwei, "He seemed to be more anxious than before and spoke at a faster pace. At first I couldn't hear what he said, but later I realized that he didn't know how to go on this stretch of road in Anhui. " The astronauts didn't dock the motorcade, it is presumed that Yan Yiwei was at that time "in a desperate situation, " and his number belonged to Anhui. Yan Yiwei may have noticed this, so he came to ask if he could provide resources in Anhui.

Yan chengang's mother had just finished her confinement, and the phone calls from the volunteers also reached her cell phone. According to their tips, she went out for the first time, had a nucleic acid test, returned home and finished disinfection, and immediately called the relevant departments in Anhui Province, "finally called the emergency center, the emergency center said, because of the epidemic, ambulances have been requisitioned, there is no dispatchable vehicles. "

As well as vehicle access, hospital reception is also a problem. Yu Lulu, a staff member at the Children's Hospital affiliated to Nanjing Medical University, told Polar Day, "The nature of a hospital is to save lives, and as long as the child can come through the normal channels to our hospital, we are ready to operate on him. But how he gets there, how he does it, is up to the administration to co-ordinate and communicate."

Lv Qing has been watching the progress of the rescue, she felt, as if she had followed the case of a failed referral to another place, this case is also going into a dead end.

Sentence is too long, please supply a shorter sentence

At that time, Chen Xingxu was as desperate as she was, begging for help everywhere. "I know that there are people in the circle of friends who engage in enterprises, who engage in the media, who may have the ability and the right to make their voices heard. "

By the end of the day, things were finally moving forward.

Luck and normalcy

He Chunhui, who is in the Huazhong University of Science and Technology with Chen, responded to his message, "I'll see what I can do about this, " she said.

"As a matter of fact, I have never met Chunhui, and usually we just chat in a group. There is no special relationship between us. " Chen Xingxu saw her reply and felt a little more reassured. Before, Chunhui asked for help from the group, she is the one who provides contact information for government departments. He suspects that she has a "higher position" , but he doesn't know which unit she works in or what she does.

Half an hour later, he Chunhui called over, "she said has been docking related matters, promised to track the whole way things. "

At that time, a reporter from the Yangtze Evening News also approached Chen Xingxu to find out the details of this rescue. Chen Xingxu asked him to ask the attitude of the Children's Hospital affiliated to Nanjing Medical University, "after Chunhui Hung Up, good news came from Nanjing that the hospital had agreed to accept the child. "

He Chunhui was born in the 1960s and moved to Beijing in the 1990s, where she worked in the Ministry of the State Council for more than 20 years. Later, she went to the sea and became a senior member of the alumni group. She also contacted two students from the Huazhong University of Science and Technology, "One was a local entrepreneur in Nanjing, and the other was a member of the state-level media, and they also contacted the Nanjing Health Commission and the Children's Hospital, " he said. "We got confirmation from them again that the hospital acceptance is completely OK. As long as the hospital in Hubei issues a (transfer certificate) , the hospital in Nanjing issues a transfer certificate. As long as the child's DNA test is negative twice, he will be sent directly to the hospital. "

Chen has even found an alternative. "The reporter from Hubei Daily gave me the contact information of a helicopter company. They have a medical helicopter, high oxygen environment, with isolation chamber and Suction Machine. It is very rare and suitable for this child, but the price is expensive, it costs 300,000 yuan a trip. "

"Our group just donated some money, " he told he, while they were still worried about getting stuck on the road. "No matter how much, we'll rent it. "

By the evening of the 21st, Yan no longer had to worry about being stuck in traffic and being unable to be admitted to a hospital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
An ambulance carrying Yan chengang leaves Wuhan. Photo provided by interviewee

For the past month, he has slept only three or four hours a day, had breakfast at the hospital, and returned home after 8 p.m. for a second meal. His hometown is Xiaogan, a programmer in Wuhan, and his house is in Jiangxia District, 20 kilometers away from the provincial maternal and child health center. When the electric car ran out of electricity, he cycled to the Provincial Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine and replaced it with a shared bicycle. It's a two-hour drive.

Three days ago, when he posted on Facebook, he was prepared for the worst, "from the 13th to the 18th, I begged every day for a week, never asked so many people in my life, and in the end I felt completely hopeless and it was hard to find a way. "

But since Chen Xingxu called, difficulties have been solved one after another. The next day, the volunteers helped find an ambulance. The medical aid company Wuhan Adaxon Medical Aid Station, which can be rented, is equipped with suction machines. The asking price from Wuhan to Nanjing is 18,000 yuan. What Yan Yiwei, the accompanying family member, had to do was wait for the results of Yan's second nucleic acid test and prepare to be quarantined directly for 14 days after arriving in Nanjing.

Now the problem is solved. The 1,000-plus Mile Road from Wuhan to Nanjing, which at that time seemed impossible to cross, is thus broken through. He had no idea who had helped, "only that there were many eager volunteers. "

In the experience of Chen Xingxu and Lu Qing, it is rare to see such strong and effective assistance. Only this time, an "invisible hand" joined it, it has a strong social resources, in touch with it, the volunteers like fire burning up enthusiasm, to warm up those suffering.

"This baby is really very lucky, " Lu said. Tu Chunping, a suspected leukemia patient she followed up with, was turned away from a hospital in Hunan Province on Feb. 22.

Tu Chunping, 26, whose white blood cells are only a third of normal, was found to have suspected acute leukemia at Xiaogan's central hospital more than 10 days ago. "He needs to go to a big hospital like Tongji Hospital, Union Medical College Hospital and Zhongnan Hospital in Wuhan to get the results of the puncture test, and then confirm the diagnosis and get a treatment plan, " Tu's sister told Lu. "Now call and ask. The hospital's laboratory is not open, the test can not be done, and other hospitals in Wuhan that are treating non-new coronavirus pneumonia patients are going to ask them one by one and say they can not do it. "

On Feb. 16, she decided to take her brother to a hospital in Hunan province because she couldn't stand the bumpy road. Tu Chunping has been given a "non-pneumonia patient health certificate" , ready to quarantine the past 14 days, but also contact the local epidemic prevention headquarters to open a vehicle pass. Ready before the trip, and finally came to the hospital's exact response: "The hematology department has no spare beds. "

"Tu Chunping has been asking for help for nearly 10 days. We have tried everything we can think of, everything we can use, " Lu said, "At first they asked relatives to ask about the hospital and the hospital said it was acceptable, but now [ the hospital ] probably still doesn't want the patients from Hubei to go. Once anyone who goes out becomes the source of infection, then someone will have to bear the responsibility. Who Dares bear the responsibility? "

Save Darling and Save Wuhan

Chen Xingxu feel Yan Chengang children like the main characters in the film, they are to help him "customs" assistant.

Before putting him in the ambulance, the volunteers were unnerved and busy identifying possible obstacles on the way. On February 23, a reporter from Anhui Traffic Radio Promised Chen Xingxu, "as soon as we enter Anhui, we will be responsible for coordinating if there are any problems. " Relevant departments in Hubei Province also sent him news, "Ask them to send a message about which route to take, and they send someone to follow up. "

The uncertainty of the journey has all but disappeared, and there is only one task left before the journey on February 24th: to get Yan's second nucleic acid test report. Really can not wait, nearly 7 pm, Chen Xingxu went to request the help of Hongshan District Health Commission staff, 7:13 test results, "negative, ready to go. "

He's been texting and calling all day, his phone has been charged five times, "some people are avoiding me. Am I boring you? " He sends a "cover face" look. Nearly 72 hours had passed since he received the message, and he was now at peace with the fear that he would not make it, that the child would not survive the long wait. He Remembers Yan Yiwei to send him pictures of children, small people wrapped in a quilt, half open mouth breathing, "he is too small, must save him down. "

Such a mood for Chen Xingxu, in the days of volunteers is no more familiar.

When he was trying to find a bed for a pneumonia patient, he was overwhelmed with helpless people and News. For a while, Chen Xingxu also had a fever. "He had a dry cough that hurt his heart, liver, and lungs. He had sputum-like sputum, and his symptoms resembled those of a pneumonia patient. " But the symptoms also disappeared quickly, and he later thought it might be called psychological substitution.

And he is same, LV Qing's in the mind also accumulated layer upon layer powerless feeling. "One night I was on the phone with an old man, his wife had died of pneumonia, his daughter had gone to the hospital with severe illness, he went into isolation by himself, he cried on the phone, I was able to talk to him normally, but I knew it was a dark time for me, I went to bed very late, and as soon as I lay down, tears came out. "

After the rescue of Yan Chengang came to light, LV Qing decided not to follow up any new cases. For the past month or so, she had devoted all her energy to voluntary activities. Now, she is ready to return to a normal life, next plan to apply for reading a doctor, "finally, only hope to hear the news of the children smoothly to Nanjing. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Yan was accompanied by medical staff from the Hubei Provincial Maternal and child health hospital, who survived the 1,000-mile journey. Photo courtesy of the respondents

February 23 at 9 pm, all ready, Chen Xingxu has to participate in the relay rescue volunteers in the group to release the news ready to leave, did not expect the "clearance" on the road still have checkpoints.

At 11 p.m. , a doctor at the Hubei provincial maternal and Child Health Hospital gave Yan a physical evaluation. "The road is too far, the child is too weak, and if something goes wrong on the road and can not be dealt with, there is a 60 percent risk of the child dying. "

Chen Xingxu felt as if his heart was being held. If the provincial maternal and child health care hospital allowed Yan chengang's attending doctors and nurses to accompany him, it would greatly improve his chances of survival. Chen Xingxu went to seek the consent of the hospital leaders again. After midnight, he sent a crying expression, "agreed. [ hospitals ] support pediatricians and nurses. "

"My heart is going to explode, " he said.

Now, Yan Chengang can finally leave Wuhan and go to Nanjing for an operation.

A successful referral, but also help Chen Xingxu completed a psychological compensation, the past month, he touched more unresolved and the resulting backlog of emotions.

He's got a lot of associations. "This child was born into the world for 29 days, 29 days of life, and he suffered the same ordeal as Wuhan. His disease is called Pirow Syndrome, which is related to inhalation. He has very thin windpipes and has difficulty breathing. In fact, Wuhan seems to have the same disease. " You don't have to thank me, " he told Yan. "We didn't just save your child. We saved Wuhan. "

On February 24, at 1:00 noon, Yan chengang got into an ambulance bound for Nanjing. He was wrapped in a pink quilt and fastened his safety belt. The ambulance reached 150 yards. The road was bumpy and one of his feeding tubes was broken, fortunately, a doctor helped to change, Yan Yiwei stood up and looked at him from a distance. More than 7:00 pm, children survived the long road, arrived at the Children's Hospital affiliated to Nanjing Medical University.

From then on, the child would only have to struggle with his illness.

(at the request of the interviewee, Lu Qing was given a pseudonym.)
